                <note type="updated" update="general" import="tengyur-data-1784-1917_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2021-11-02T13:32:54.498Z" user="admin">The text of the Samantabhadra Sādhana, apart from quotations from the Guhyasamāja Tantra, appears to have been composed in the Ārya metre—a metre in which
            the number of syllables in each pada is not fixed, and is instead governed by vowel length alone. It is possible that Smṛtijñānakīrti’s method of translation, with each verse consisting of
            two lines, is his way of representing verse written in the ārya metre in Tibetan translation.</note>
